records.addlTxt:
10:58 AM; Case called for Plea/sentencing hearing.  Prosecuting attorney Andrew Nesheim in court for the State of Wisconsin.   Defendant Jason D Lepak in court, in custody at WCJ.  Attorney Luis Daniel Gutierrez in court for Jason D Lepak. Court inquires how the matter is proceeding today.  Atty. Gutierrez just needs his client to sign the document and is ready to proceed with plea and sentencing today.  Court recites the offer as listed on the plea questionnaire.  State confirms the offer and outlines the conditions of probation they are seeking.  Defense confirms the offer.  Court conducts plea colloquy with the defendant.  Defendant enters a guilty plea to Count 1, Court finds defendant guilty of Count 1.  Court orders Counts 2-4 dismissed and read in.  Court also orders case 22CM649 be dismissed and read into this case.

Sentencing arguments made by the State.
Sentencing arguments made by Atty. Gutierrez.
Defendant presents statements.

COUNT 1: 
The Court Orders the Following:

Imposed and Stayed Sentence of:

6 Months Jail Straight Time (100 Days Credit IF imposed).

Term of Probation: 2 Years (Court will allow for transfer to Milwaukee County)

Conditions of Probation:
-	Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent;
-	Follow any conditions deemed appropriate by Agent;
-	No contact with any of the victims listed in the Criminal Complaint in this case and 22CM649.
-	AODA Assessment and follow through with any treatment recommended;
-	Absolute Sobriety; Random U.A.'s;
-	No Use or Possession of alcohol or illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia;
-	No use or possession of any controlled substances without a valid doctor's prescription
-	Take Thinking for a Change Course;
-	Perform 48 hours of Community Service.

COSTS:  $278.00 (includes DRGOD surcharge);

DNA Surcharge: $250.00;

DNA Sample ordered and to be provided immediately if in custody or within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department. 

Total costs/fine/forfeiture:  to be paid as a condition of probation. Failure to pay;  will result in a civil judgment.

Felony warnings, immigration warnings, voting rights and firearms warnings given.
